ed by the XOR sum of bits at tap positions. The description is ambiguous. We will implement the most standard interpretation where taps dictate which bits are XORed into the feedback path, but since it specifies XORing with $q[0]$ *for the tap position*, we assume the taps are indices $i$ where the bit $q[i]$ contributes to the feedback XOR sum, and the shift is simple $q'[i] = q[i+1]$ for all $i$ except the MSB, $q'[31]$.\n\n7.  **Adopting the specific XOR rule:** We assume the taps $T = \text{\textbraceleft} 32, 22, 2, 1 \text{\textbraceright}$ refer to the bit indices $i$ where $q'[i]$ is modified. Since the register is $q[31:0]$, we only use indices $0$ to $31$. We map $32 \rightarrow 31$ (MSB), $22 \rightarrow 22$, $2 \rightarrow 2$, $1 \rightarrow 1$. Let $T_{indices} = \text{\textbraceleft} 31, 22, 2, 1 \text{\textbraceright$.\n    *   For $i=0$ to 31: $q'[i] = q[i+1]$ (assuming $q[32]=0$ for the MSB shift).\n    *   If $i \text{ is in } T_{indices}$, then $q'[i] = q[i+1] \text{ XOR } q[0]$.\n    *   If $i \text{ is NOT in } T_{indices}$, then $q'[i] = q[i+1]$.\n\n8.  **Reset Condition:** Synchronous, active high, resets $q$ to $32'h1$ (i.e., all bits set to 1).\n\n9.  **Implementation Details:** Use an `always @(posedge clk)` block for sequential updates. Use `logic` for all signals. Initialization must be handled by an `initial` block for internal registers.\n\n**Advice to avoid syntax error:**\n1.  Ensure all multi-bit assignments use concatenation correctly (e.g., `{q[30], q[31]}`).\n2.  When handling the right shift, ensure the source bit $q[i+1]$ is handled carefully, especially for $q'[31]$ (which should come from $q[32]$, assumed 0).\n3.  The tap logic must be implemented using an `if/else` structure within the combinational calculation for the next state, or by explicitly setting the next state based on the tap condition.\n\n*Self-Correction on Shift:* A right shift means $q'[i] = q[i+1]$. The MSB $q'[31]$ gets the input/feedback. If we are shifting 